abstract: The act of last Legislature amending the Game law of last year, contains one point of considerable interest to sportsmen. This is contained in the clause changing the day for commencing to shoot woodcock from the 15th to the 3d of July. The amendment in question restores this point of the law to what it was before 1871, and is regarded with considerable satisfaction by the entire fraternity of sportsmen.

abstract: Several trade societies, exclusively German, met yesterday, and discussed the eighthour question. Below we give a report of the proceedings.
headline: {'main': 'THE GERMAN STRIKERS.; The Printers, the Engineers, the Fresco Painters, the Clothing-Cutters and Other Trades. THE GERMAN ENGINERRS MOVING FOR AN INCREASE OF WAGES. THE GERMAN FRESCO PAINTERS DEMAND EIGHT HOURS. THE CLOTHING-CUTTERS. ACTION BY OTHER GERMAN TRADES-UNIONS. The German comfectioners held a meeting at No. 77 Allen-street yesterday, to organize and demand the eight hour system. The case-makers met for the same purpose at the Walhall, in Orchard-street. The carpenters of Harlem met on Saturday night at Germania Hall, in One Hundred and Twentyfifth-street, and formed a trades-union.The hat and cap makers met at No. 46 Avenue A to organize for the eight-hour reform, and for that purpose also formed a union. The cigarbox-makers resolved to strike for the eight-hourrule today.
